  "prompt": "What does add on item on Amazon mean?",
  "response": "On Amazon, an **\"Add-on Item\"** refers to a low-priced product that customers can include in their orders as long as the total value of the order meets a certain minimum threshold (typically around $25, though this can vary). These items are designed to be inexpensive enough that they might not qualify for free shipping on their own, but when combined with other purchases, they can be shipped together cost-effectively.\n\n**Key Features of Add-on Items:**\n\n1. **Minimum Order Requirement:** To purchase add-on items, the overall order must usually meet a minimum spend. This ensures that the combined shipping costs remain economical.\n\n2. **Eligible Products:** Not all products qualify as add-on items. Typically, these are smaller, lighter, and lower-priced products that are easy to ship and complement other items in a customer's cart.\n\n3. **Free Shipping:** Add-on items often benefit from free shipping when added to a qualifying order. However, if a customer is not already eligible for free shipping (e.g., they aren't a Prime member or haven't met the free shipping threshold), the add-on item may not ship until the overall order meets the minimum requirement.\n\n4. **Visibility to Sellers:** For sellers on Amazon, designating a product as an add-on item can help increase its visibility and sales by making it available to a broader range of customers looking to add affordable extras to their purchases.\n\n**Benefits for Customers:**\n\n- **Cost-Effective:** Customers can add smaller items to their orders without worrying about incurring high shipping costs for those individual products.\n  \n- **Convenience:** It simplifies the shopping process by allowing customers to bundle necessary small items with their larger purchases.\n\n**Benefits for Sellers:**\n\n- **Increased Sales Opportunities:** By categorizing products as add-on items, sellers can encourage impulse buys and increase the average order value.\n  \n- **Enhanced Product Visibility:** Add-on items are showcased to a wider audience who might be looking to complement their main purchases.\n\n**Examples of Add-on Items:**\n\n- Accessories like phone chargers or screen protectors.\n- Consumables such as vitamins or small beauty products.\n- Household items like sponges or small kitchen gadgets.\n\n**How to Identify Add-on Items on Amazon:**\n\nWhen browsing Amazon, add-on items typically have a label or indication stating \"Add-on Item\" or similar phrasing on the product listing page. Additionally, during the checkout process, customers will be informed if adding a specific item requires meeting the minimum order threshold.\n\n**Conclusion:**\n\nAdd-on items are a strategic feature on Amazon designed to enhance the shopping experience for customers by offering affordable products that can be conveniently added to larger orders. For sellers, it's an opportunity to market supplementary products and boost overall sales.",
